  "response_text": "Here's a daily routine to help improve your balance and focus:\n\n**Morning Routine (15-20 minutes)**\n\n1. **Neck Stretch**: Slowly tilt your head to the side, bringing your ear towards your shoulder. Hold for 30 seconds and then switch sides.\n2. **Shoulder Rolls**: Roll your shoulders forward and backward in a circular motion. Repeat for 30 seconds.\n3. **Leg Swings**: Stand with your feet hip-width apart and swing one leg forward and backward, then switch to the other leg. Repeat for 30 seconds on each leg.\n4. **Single-Leg Stance**: Stand on one leg, keeping the other foot lifted off the ground. Hold for 30 seconds and then switch legs. This will help improve your balance and stability.\n5. **Deep Breathing Exercises**: Sit comfortably with your eyes closed and focus on deep, slow breaths. Inhale for 4 seconds, hold for 4 seconds, and exhale for 4 seconds. Repeat for 5 minutes.\n\n**Balance Exercises (10-15 minutes, 3 times a week)**\n\n1. **Single-Leg Squats**: Stand on one leg and slowly lower your body into a squat. Hold for a few seconds and then stand up. Repeat on the other leg.\n2. **Heel-To-Toe Walking**: Walk along a straight line, placing the heel of one foot directly in front of the toes of the other foot.\n3. **Balance Boards or BOSU Ball**: Stand on a balance board or BOSU ball with your feet shoulder-width apart. Hold for 30 seconds to a minute, rest, and then repeat.\n4. **Tree Pose**: Stand on one leg, with the other foot resting against your inner thigh. Hold for 30 seconds to a minute, rest, and then repeat on the other leg.\n\n**Focus Exercises (10-15 minutes, 3 times a week)**\n\n1. **Meditation**: Sit comfortably with your eyes closed and focus on a single point, such as your breath or a mantra. Start with 5-minute sessions and gradually increase the time.\n2. **Concentration Exercises**: Focus on a small object, such as a pen or a coin, and try to maintain your attention on it for 30 seconds to a minute.\n3. **Puzzle or Brain Teaser**: Engage in a puzzle or brain teaser, such as a crossword or Sudoku, to challenge your focus and problem-solving skills.\n4. **Mindful Walking**: Take a short walk while focusing on your surroundings, including the sights, sounds, and sensations in your body.\n\n**Evening Routine (10-15 minutes)**\n\n1. **Stretching**: Engage in some light stretching to relax your muscles and improve flexibility.\n2. **Gratitude Reflection**: Reflect on your day and think about the things you're grateful for.\n3. **Deep Breathing Exercises**: Repeat the deep breathing exercises from the morning routine to help calm your mind and body before bed.\n\nRemember to start slowly and gradually increase the duration and intensity of your routine as you become more comfortable with the exercises. It's also essential to listen to your body and rest when needed. Consult with a healthcare professional before starting any new exercise routine.",
